<paragraph id="8BCA36D7FFC6A706FF2FFCDCA69AC1A8" blockId="5.[136,1452,158,905]" pageId="5" pageNumber="91">
Remarks:— 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D54FFC6A706FED7FCDCA614C13C" authorityName="Antonin, R. Ryoo &amp; K. H. Ka" authorityYear="2014" box="[325,618,770,796]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Crinipellis" kingdom="Fungi" order="Agaricales" pageId="5" pageNumber="91" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="birhizomorpha">
<emphasis id="B901EAC5FFC6A706FED7FCDCA614C13C" box="[325,618,770,796]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="91">Crinipellis birhizomorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized as having a rather small pileus, a rather short stipe arising from both substrate and rhizomorphs, a context with farinaceous-fungoid smell, rhizomorphs of 
<specimenCount id="9D73FD5EFFC6A706FB3EFCF9A164C161" box="[1196,1306,807,833]" pageId="5" pageNumber="91" type="generic" typeStatus="types">two types</specimenCount>
, one forming abortive pilei, moderately large, non-dextrinoid, rarely slightly dextrinoid basidiospores, cheilocystidia in the form of broom cells, no pleurocystidia, and growing on twigs.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF0A665FFFC6A706FF1AF80BA531CA2F" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138973" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5138973" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138973/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="91" startId="5.[136,229,2005,2027]" targetBox="[464,1091,928,1955]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph id="8BCA36D7FFC6A706FF1AF80BA531CA2F" blockId="5.[136,1452,2005,2063]" pageId="5" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis id="B901EAC5FFC6A706FF1AF80BA480C5CA" bold="true" box="[136,254,2005,2027]" pageId="5" pageNumber="91">FIGURE 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C754D54FFC6A706FE96F80BA67EC5CA" authorityName="Antonin, R. Ryoo &amp; K. H. Ka" authorityYear="2014" box="[260,512,2005,2026]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Crinipellis" kingdom="Fungi" order="Agaricales" pageId="5" pageNumber="91" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="birhizomorpha">
<emphasis id="B901EAC5FFC6A706FE96F80BA67EC5CA" box="[260,512,2005,2026]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="91">Crinipellis birhizomorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. a. cheilocystidia, b. basidiospores, c. pileus hairs, d. surface of abortive pilei. Scale bar = 20 μm for a–c, 50 μm for d.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BCA36D7FFC5A705FF2FFF40A7C5C394" blockId="6.[136,1452,158,437]" pageId="6" pageNumber="92">
The presence of the second 
<typeStatus id="54CE8875FFC5A705FE67FF41A65BC299" box="[501,549,159,185]" pageId="6" pageNumber="92">type</typeStatus>
of rhizomorphs with an erect, narrowly clavate upper part, terminating in brown abortive pilei is a rather unique character in 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D54FFC5A705FD0FFF1CA76BC2FC" authorityName="Patouillard" authorityYear="1889" box="[669,789,194,220]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Crinipellis" kingdom="Fungi" order="Agaricales" pageId="6" pageNumber="92" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B901EAC5FFC5A705FD0FFF1CA76BC2FC" box="[669,789,194,220]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="92">Crinipellis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Only one species having such rhizomorphs, 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D54FFC5A705FAA6FF1CA644C321" authority="Kerekes et al. (2009: 116)" authorityName="Kerekes" authorityPageNumber="116" authorityYear="2009" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Crinipellis" kingdom="Fungi" order="Agaricales" pageId="6" pageNumber="92" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="cupreostipes">
<emphasis id="B901EAC5FFC5A705FAA6FF1CA56BC320" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="92">Crinipellis cupreostipes</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B26FFC5A705FE88FF38A644C321" author="Kerekes, J. F. &amp; Desjardin, D. E." box="[282,570,230,257]" pageId="6" pageNumber="92" pagination="101 - 152" refId="ref11760" refString="Kerekes, J. F. &amp; Desjardin, D. E. (2009) A monograph of the genera Crinipellis and Moniliophthora from Southeast Asia including a molecular phylogeny of the nrITS region. Fungal Diversity 37: 101 - 152." type="journal article" year="2009">
Kerekes 
<emphasis id="B901EAC5FFC5A705FEEEFF39A5CDC320" box="[380,435,230,256]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="92">et al.</emphasis>
(2009: 116)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is found in the literature. This species differs in having a copper-coloured stipe, longer and narrower basidiospores with a different Q value (9–11 × 
<quantity id="4C8D9B32FFC5A705FC17FED4A78DC305" box="[901,1011,266,293]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.25" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="4.25" valueMax="4.5" valueMin="4.0">4–4.5 µm</quantity>
, Q = 2.4) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B26FFC5A705FBFFFED4A1DEC304" author="Kerekes, J. F. &amp; Desjardin, D. E." box="[1133,1440,266,292]" pageId="6" pageNumber="92" pagination="101 - 152" refId="ref11760" refString="Kerekes, J. F. &amp; Desjardin, D. E. (2009) A monograph of the genera Crinipellis and Moniliophthora from Southeast Asia including a molecular phylogeny of the nrITS region. Fungal Diversity 37: 101 - 152." type="journal article" year="2009">Kerekes &amp; Desjardin 2009</bibRefCitation>
). For a discussion of other similar taxa not forming abortive pilei and stipes arising from rhizomorphs, see notes in this paper about 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D54FFC5A705FE87FE8DA5C7C34C" authorityName="Antonin, R. Ryoo &amp; K. H. Ka" authorityYear="2014" box="[277,441,338,365]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Crinipellis" kingdom="Fungi" order="Agaricales" pageId="6" pageNumber="92" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="wandoensis">
<emphasis id="B901EAC5FFC5A705FE87FE8DA5C7C34C" box="[277,441,338,365]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="92">C. wandoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D54FFC5A705FE5AFE8CA74BC34C" authority="Kerekes et al." authorityName="Kerekes" box="[456,821,338,364]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Crinipellis" kingdom="Fungi" order="Agaricales" pageId="6" pageNumber="92" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="tabtim">
<emphasis id="B901EAC5FFC5A705FE5AFE8CA6EEC34C" box="[456,656,338,364]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="92">Crinipellis tabtim</emphasis>
Kerekes 
<emphasis id="B901EAC5FFC5A705FD6EFE8DA74BC34C" box="[764,821,338,364]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="92">et al.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is phylogeneticaly placed close to 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D54FFC5A705FB51FE8DA1F5C34C" authorityName="Antonin, R. Ryoo &amp; K. H. Ka" authorityYear="2014" box="[1219,1419,338,365]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Crinipellis" kingdom="Fungi" order="Agaricales" pageId="6" pageNumber="92" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="birhizomorpha">
<emphasis id="B901EAC5FFC5A705FB51FE8DA1F5C34C" box="[1219,1419,338,365]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="92">C. birhizomorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs in a violet-brown to dark ruby coloured pileus, the absence of rhizomorphs, larger basidiospores (8–11 × 
<quantity id="4C8D9B32FFC5A705FAFEFEA8A4CFC395" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.75" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="4.75" valueMax="5.5" valueMin="4.0">4–5.5 µm</quantity>
), and only 
<quantity id="4C8D9B32FFC5A705FEBCFE44A5D1C395" box="[302,431,410,437]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="0.7" pageId="6" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="105.0" valueMax="140.0" valueMin="70.0">70–140 µm</quantity>
long pileus hairs (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B26FFC5A705FDEFFE44A7D1C394" author="Kerekes, J. F. &amp; Desjardin, D. E." box="[637,943,410,436]" pageId="6" pageNumber="92" pagination="101 - 152" refId="ref11760" refString="Kerekes, J. F. &amp; Desjardin, D. E. (2009) A monograph of the genera Crinipellis and Moniliophthora from Southeast Asia including a molecular phylogeny of the nrITS region. Fungal Diversity 37: 101 - 152." type="journal article" year="2009">Kerekes &amp; Desjardin 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
